<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P20">Of those with a recorded SPMSQ, 350 (17.8%) had cognitive impairment and were balanced between zoledronic acid (n=168 [48%]) and placebo (n=182 [52%]) arms. Baseline characteristics for participants with normal and impaired cognitive function are shown in <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>. Patients with cognitive impairment were significantly older, less likely to be Caucasian, had a lower BMI and a higher Charlson co-morbidity index, but were more likely to have been users of concomitant anti-osteoporosis medications. Those with cognitive impairment who had baseline bone density measurements also had lower bone density at both the total hip and femoral neck.</p>
